AIM

To demonstrate basic dictionary operations in Python such as accessing values, retrieving keys and values, updating elements, checking length, copying dictionary, clearing elements and iterating through dictionary items.

Algorithm

Start the program.
Create a dictionary named students containing name, age, course and city.
Create another dictionary named marks containing subject marks.
Access and display values from the dictionary using keys.
Display all keys from the dictionary.
Display all values from the dictionary.
Display key-value pairs using items().
Find the length of the dictionary.
Update a value in the dictionary.
Create a copy of the dictionary.
Loop through the dictionary and print each key.
Stop the program.

SOURCE CODE
students = {"name":"Roy","age":21,"course":"Python","city":"Bangalore"}

marks = {"math":78,"science":88,"english":67,"history":90}

print("Student name:", students["name"])

print("Student age:", students.get("age"))

print("Dictionary keys:", students.keys())

print("Dictionary values:", students.values())

print("Dictionary items:", students.items())

print("Length of dictionary:", len(students))

students.update({"age":22})
print("Updated dictionary:", students)

print("Copied dictionary:", students.copy())

print("Marks keys:", marks.keys())

print("Marks values:", marks.values())

print("Looping through dictionary:")
for key in students:
    print(key, students[key])
